th meaning ‘the fortified place’ from Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified (place)’ + <i>stōw</i> ‘assembly place’.","English:"]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Bristowe was born in 1390, in Selby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sir Hugh Bristowe and Mrs Hugh Bristowe. She married Walter Selby about 1409. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1413, at the age of 23."},"et":{"1390–1413":"1390–1413","1382–1443":"1382–1443","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","about 1409":"umbes 1409","1413":"1413","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","about 1410":"umbes 1410","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1382":"1382","before 1390":"enne 1390","1390":"1390","Selby, Yorkshire, England":"Selby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Selby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Selby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1390–1413":"1390–1413","1382–1443":"1382–1443","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1409":"noin 1409","1413":"1413","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","about 1410":"noin 1410","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1382":"1382","before 1390":"ennen vuotta 1390","1390":"1390","Selby, Yorkshire, England":"Selby, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Selby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Selby, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1390–1413":"1390–1413","1382–1443":"1382–1443","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","about 1409":"environ 1409","1413":"1413","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","about 1410":"environ 1410","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1382":"1382","before 1390":"avant 13